05:29.195 --> 05:32.645
[SPEAKER_34]: $4.5 million of stolen cargo is recovered.

05:33.247 --> 05:40.728
[SPEAKER_34]: San Fernando Gardens gets climate resilient and there's a new general manager at the city's El Pueblo Historical Monument.

05:40.748 --> 05:43.035
[SPEAKER_34]: These stories up next on City Beat.

05:49.428 --> 06:00.605
[SPEAKER_36]: The Los Angeles Police Department's Commercial Crimes Division announced the seizure of $4.5 million in stolen property and the arrest of a key individual for retail and cargo theft.

06:01.106 --> 06:13.225
[SPEAKER_36]: LAPD worked with LA Port Police and Union Pacific Police to recover tools, appliances, e-bikes and other items, which were being fenced through a storefront and online platforms.

06:13.205 --> 06:23.162
[SPEAKER_36]: According to LAPD Chief Jim McDonald, protecting the integrity of the supply chain is vital to public safety as well as the economic stability of Los Angeles.

06:23.743 --> 06:31.657
[SPEAKER_36]: Anyone with information on retail or cargo crime is urged to contact Crimestoppers, where tips can be reported anonymously.

06:32.118 --> 06:36.225
[SPEAKER_36]: For more information, visit LAPDOnline.org.

06:38.585 --> 06:46.340
[SPEAKER_36]: L.A. City Housing Authority, HACLA, was joined by Congresswoman Rivas to tour new energy-efficient upgrades at San Fernando Gardens.

06:47.081 --> 06:55.918
[SPEAKER_36]: Federal funds of $3.5 million are being used to bring more sustainable and resilient living conditions to nearly 1,500 residents.

06:55.898 --> 07:05.008
[SPEAKER_36]: HACLA is installing 448 energy-efficient air conditioning units donated by the Office of Mayor Bass and the L.A. Department of Water and Power.

07:05.609 --> 07:15.379
[SPEAKER_36]: The community center at San Fernando Gardens has also been upgraded to serve as a resiliency center with backup solar power energy in case of a heat emergency.

07:16.060 --> 07:25.450
[SPEAKER_36]: According to HACLA, extreme weather adversely impacts the San Fernando Valley, and these enhancements will improve the quality of life for public housing residents.

07:25.430 --> 07:28.369
[SPEAKER_36]: For more information, visit hackla.org.

07:30.678 --> 07:39.246
[SPEAKER_36]: LA City Council has confirmed Dominica Lynch as the new general manager of El Pueblo Historical Monument and its first Latina leader.

07:39.266 --> 07:49.615
[SPEAKER_36]: A graduate of the University of Southern California, Lynch has more than 20 years experience in nonprofit organizations supporting Latino and other underrepresented communities.

07:50.376 --> 08:00.685
[SPEAKER_36]: According to Mayor Bass, El Pueblo's leader needs to preserve its history and activate business and event space, especially during this challenging time for immigrant communities.

08:00.665 --> 08:04.642
[SPEAKER_36]: Lynch will begin as general manager of El Pueblo on October 20th.

08:05.204 --> 08:10.185
[SPEAKER_36]: For more information, visit mayor.lacity.gov slash press.

08:17.590 --> 08:24.682
[SPEAKER_34]: Councilwoman Heather Hutt celebrated with community members as the city designated the home of Tom Bradley, a historical monument.

08:25.283 --> 08:32.275
[SPEAKER_34]: This was just one of a series of African American landmarks being honored, adding to the rich cultural tapestry of Los Angeles.

08:35.242 --> 08:36.423
[SPEAKER_41]: It's so exciting.

08:36.443 --> 08:38.525
[SPEAKER_41]: We're at the home of Tom Bradley.

08:38.726 --> 08:45.273
[SPEAKER_41]: He was a mayor for 20 years in Los Angeles and he was the council member right here in the 10th district first.

08:45.293 --> 08:51.259
[SPEAKER_41]: We're in Lamarque Park and what we've done is designated his home as a historical monument.

08:51.659 --> 09:03.612
[SPEAKER_41]: His children are here and they've been able to talk about their experience growing up in a community that wasn't really as multicultural as it is today.

09:03.592 --> 09:10.829
[SPEAKER_41]: And then coming from that, we're going to St. Elmo's Village to talk about youth's contributions to this city.

09:11.270 --> 09:18.867
[SPEAKER_41]: And then we're moving to Catch One, which was Jules Tyus Williams' big club for LGBTQ community.

09:21.648 --> 09:31.242
[SPEAKER_20]: The African American Historic Places LA project is a joint project between the City of Los Angeles' Office of Historic Resources and the Getty Conservation Institute.

09:31.642 --> 09:39.353
[SPEAKER_20]: So some of these sites that we are designating are not architecturally significant or have an architecturally high style, so you could miss them.

09:39.704 --> 09:50.328
[SPEAKER_20]: St. Omo Village is an artist enclave, a set of 10 bungalows that were created by Roderick and Rozelle Sykes because they were shunned from the art world.

09:50.509 --> 09:55.340
[SPEAKER_20]: They couldn't get their paintings sold in mainstream white art institutions.

09:55.741 --> 09:58.928
[SPEAKER_20]: And they also wanted an opportunity for anybody.

09:58.908 --> 10:01.652
[SPEAKER_20]: people of color, anybody to have access to art.

10:01.972 --> 10:08.461
[SPEAKER_20]: And then Catch One, sadly, we lost Jules, who is the owner and creator of Catch One.

10:08.742 --> 10:13.829
[SPEAKER_20]: And she opened the first black gay disco in the United States.

10:13.849 --> 10:17.974
[SPEAKER_20]: And that was also during a time where folks were still ostracized.

10:18.315 --> 10:20.958
[SPEAKER_20]: So that club became a haven for everyone.

10:21.519 --> 10:27.868
[SPEAKER_20]: It's a symbol of hope for the LGBTQ plus community now, and it still operates as a dance club.

10:29.452 --> 10:37.125
[SPEAKER_20]: So if you walk down the Tom and Ethel Bradley residence and that plaque wasn't there or the signage wasn't there, you would think that it was an ordinary home.

10:37.186 --> 10:39.610
[SPEAKER_20]: It is an ordinary home, but it has an extraordinary story.

10:41.613 --> 10:48.946
[SPEAKER_20]: Tina's family bought this house at a time where there were restrictive covenants, where non-whites couldn't live in the community.

10:49.247 --> 10:54.075
[SPEAKER_20]: So they broke barriers, not only broke barriers in the community, but broke barriers in the police force.

10:55.422 --> 10:57.267
[SPEAKER_43]: My sister and family moved here.

10:57.327 --> 11:06.071
[SPEAKER_43]: My parents, brave as they were to make that move in 1950 to come to this area where we were not appreciated, where we were actually hated.

11:06.613 --> 11:11.085
[SPEAKER_42]: Riding down the street and seeing all the neighbors come out waving and

11:11.065 --> 11:11.807
[SPEAKER_42]: I was afraid.

11:12.248 --> 11:14.673
[SPEAKER_42]: Like my mother said, she didn't know what she was driving up into.

11:14.974 --> 11:19.363
[SPEAKER_43]: Took the neighbors a long time to come to the realization that we were just like them.

11:20.005 --> 11:27.100
[SPEAKER_43]: And because of it, there's a whole generation out there that are benefiting from the courage that mom and dad had.

11:30.337 --> 11:35.190
[SPEAKER_41]: So we're just showing what historical locations we have in the 10th district.

11:35.511 --> 11:46.219
[SPEAKER_41]: It's a very exciting day, especially for folks that have worked hard to commemorate these spaces at a time where so much of our history is trying to be erased.

11:54.012 --> 12:00.993
