13:35.994 --> 13:36.195
I love it.

13:36.215 --> 13:36.957
And it also has a nice swimming pool.

13:36.977 --> 13:37.217
It's lovely.

13:37.237 --> 13:37.558
[SPEAKER_26]: It's really fun.

13:37.578 --> 13:37.779
[SPEAKER_26]: I love it.

13:37.799 --> 13:37.999
[SPEAKER_26]: I love it.

13:46.552 --> 13:49.216
[SPEAKER_24]: So all of our pool parties are free to the community.

13:49.577 --> 13:53.203
[SPEAKER_24]: You know, we want to get as many people introduced to our aquatic facilities.

13:53.303 --> 14:05.623
[SPEAKER_24]: We want everybody to know that they have a pool in their neighborhood and we want them to feel supported and we want them to be introduced to a lot of our programs to make them feel safe and mainly to educate them on water safety.

14:16.032 --> 14:19.662
[SPEAKER_34]: Sex trafficking of minors is taking place in parts of Los Angeles.

14:20.084 --> 14:25.599
[SPEAKER_34]: LA City Attorney Heidi Feldstein Soto has made disrupting the demand her top priority.

14:26.141 --> 14:30.413
[SPEAKER_34]: She highlights a number of tactics being brought to bear on those committing these crimes.

14:35.641 --> 14:51.147
[SPEAKER_51]: I came into this office and I was surprised at what I found in terms of how human beings treat our young people and our kids.

14:51.167 --> 15:00.703
[SPEAKER_51]: And my first project in collaboration with Mayor Bass and Councilmember Marquise Harris-Dawson was focused on the sex trafficking of minors.

15:02.692 --> 15:10.640
[SPEAKER_51]: Protecting our children and sort of finding ways to stop the exploitation and abuse of our kids has been one of my top priorities.

15:16.006 --> 15:21.351
[SPEAKER_51]: I focused on what's known as the kiddie stroll, K-I-D-D-I-E, about little children.

15:22.072 --> 15:26.877
[SPEAKER_51]: And these are kids who are taken out and paraded on the street for sex.

15:31.008 --> 15:37.485
[SPEAKER_51]: In the Figueroa Street Initiative, we have rescued over 200 minor children, the youngest of whom was 12.

15:38.087 --> 15:42.839
[SPEAKER_51]: And we've provided, delivered them into the hands of service providers and helped them get off the streets.

15:43.662 --> 15:47.211
[SPEAKER_51]: We've also focused on shutting down the motels.

15:47.191 --> 15:51.840
[SPEAKER_51]: that are crime magnets and who don't bring themselves into compliance with applicable law.

15:52.722 --> 16:01.620
[SPEAKER_51]: And on arresting felons, predators, pimps, we've referred, I think, 74 cases to the U.S. attorney or the D.A.'

16:01.600 --> 16:03.985
[SPEAKER_51]: 's office for prosecution.

16:03.965 --> 16:10.116
[SPEAKER_51]: And probably one of my favorite things that I learned in the course of this initiative is we send out Dear John letters.

16:10.758 --> 16:19.594
[SPEAKER_51]: So part of our effort is to disrupt the demand from the adult men who were there to purchase sex from a young child.

16:19.574 --> 16:22.258
[SPEAKER_51]: and we have surveillance cameras.

16:22.318 --> 16:31.271
[SPEAKER_51]: We get a picture or a photograph of the automobile with the license plate and of the man basically doing the transaction for sexual services.

16:31.872 --> 16:40.885
[SPEAKER_51]: And we send the photograph and a letter to the registered owner of the vehicle saying, dear registered owner, your car has been seen in an area known for human trafficking of minors.

16:41.226 --> 16:44.731
[SPEAKER_51]: Please be aware we're conducting operations in the area and be more careful.

16:45.592 --> 16:48.096
[SPEAKER_51]: The registered owner is usually the spouse.

16:50.084 --> 17:00.838
[SPEAKER_51]: And we're going to stop the illegal streetwalking trafficking of our kids on Figueroa and on what's known as the Sepulveda Track in the Valley.

17:01.560 --> 17:03.165
[SPEAKER_51]: For the parents of children,

17:04.394 --> 17:08.861
[SPEAKER_51]: where the parents think there may have been abused, please report it to the LAPD.

17:09.502 --> 17:16.031
[SPEAKER_51]: They have officers trained in working with very young victims, and they will get it into the right hands.

17:16.392 --> 17:22.461
[SPEAKER_51]: If you're undocumented and you're not comfortable reporting it to the LAPD, my office has a helpline.

17:23.102 --> 17:27.448
[SPEAKER_51]: We have a program that's dedicated to children exposed to violence.

17:27.428 --> 17:31.278
[SPEAKER_51]: I note that I am the first female city attorney.

17:31.639 --> 17:33.964
[SPEAKER_51]: I'm the first Latina elected citywide.

17:34.546 --> 17:38.997
[SPEAKER_51]: And so many of our young victims are black and brown girls.

17:39.558 --> 17:43.007
[SPEAKER_51]: From my perspective, there is no higher calling.

17:42.987 --> 17:51.645
[SPEAKER_51]: to a prosecutor, then protecting the vulnerable, then being sure that justice prevails.

17:52.446 --> 18:02.447
[SPEAKER_51]: And when you're talking about little kids, they don't have their own voice without help from their families and without help from prosecutors like me.

18:02.427 --> 18:17.854
[SPEAKER_51]: And so from day one in the office, really sending out a message that abuse of children and specifically sexual abuse of children will not be tolerated, not in the city of L.A. and not by the city attorney.

18:23.977 --> 18:28.566
[SPEAKER_34]: A face-to-face community space that exposes arts and music to all.

18:29.208 --> 18:37.885
[SPEAKER_34]: At the William Grand Still Arts Center, people can be themselves and become part of a greater collective, reflecting the community and supporting local artists.

19:09.337 --> 19:33.673
[SPEAKER_11]: The mission behind the William Bresto Arts Center is one that is based in art and music exposure to the community, very intergenerational in our programming that includes yearly exhibitions, there's concerts, film screening, workshops, after school classes, all into sharing about art and music in the community.

19:34.700 --> 19:42.920
[SPEAKER_17]: You learn from everyone, whether that be the Black Doll Show, the African American Composer Series, working with youth as well.

19:42.940 --> 19:51.882
[SPEAKER_17]: So we're constantly learning from each other and I think that's something really beautiful about the center and what Stacy creates for the community.

19:56.452 --> 20:16.671
[SPEAKER_19]: One of the great things about our community art center is that we allow the community to be themselves as they are, using the language and vernacular that's local, using the codes and cues that are local, but also tapping into a greater discourse that's national and international.

20:16.651 --> 20:30.512
[SPEAKER_11]: The programming that is offered and the way that it is offered, it can foster relationships, but also just having a face-to-face space to come to, to convene, to find solace.

20:31.634 --> 20:33.276
[SPEAKER_11]: Yes, it's important.

20:35.011 --> 20:40.760
[SPEAKER_17]: I really admire this center and have much love for the center for the space it creates.

20:41.260 --> 20:48.651
[SPEAKER_17]: Having a physical space that offers things that are tangible, you're able to connect with others.

20:50.735 --> 21:02.352
[SPEAKER_19]: So one of the things that's really important about a community arts facility, it is actually owned by the people of Los Angeles, meaning that the people of Los Angeles know and get exactly what they want.

21:02.450 --> 21:03.894
[SPEAKER_19]: It's an added resource.

21:04.395 --> 21:07.041
[SPEAKER_19]: It's exhibitions that feature local artists.

21:07.362 --> 21:08.966
[SPEAKER_19]: So we want to continue this.

21:09.086 --> 21:10.470
[SPEAKER_19]: We want to foster this.

21:10.490 --> 21:19.412
[SPEAKER_19]: LA has been the place that a lot of artists have come out of and it will continue to be as long as we support community facilities like these.

21:26.868 --> 21:31.656
[SPEAKER_34]: In this week's Things to Do, Los Angeles Libros Festival celebrates much more than books.

21:32.157 --> 21:39.509
[SPEAKER_34]: Go arm-in-arm to the Festival of Philippine Arts and Culture and join the City of LA for El Grito 2025.

21:39.969 --> 21:42.193
[SPEAKER_34]: All this up next on Things to Do.

21:48.805 --> 21:56.253
[SPEAKER_36]: The Los Angeles Public Library invites you to read, dream, and celebrate with them for the Los Angeles Libros Festival.

21:56.934 --> 22:02.600
[SPEAKER_36]: Now in its seventh year, the Libros Festival is a free bilingual book festival for the whole family.

22:03.261 --> 22:12.130
[SPEAKER_36]: The celebration creates an inclusive cultural space to engage and inspire current and future generations of bilingual Angelenos.

22:12.110 --> 22:23.346
[SPEAKER_36]: With 16 authors appearing during the day, there'll be entertainment and fun with Spanish language and bilingual storytelling, musical performances, workshops, readings, and community.

22:23.866 --> 22:37.425
[SPEAKER_36]: Head to Downtown's Central Library for the Los Angeles Libros Festival on Saturday, September 13th, from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. For more information, visit lapl.org slash Libros.

22:39.734 --> 22:46.261
[SPEAKER_36]: Join LA City's Department of Cultural Affairs and Phil M. Arts for the Festival of Philippine Arts and Culture.

22:46.302 --> 22:53.730
[SPEAKER_36]: This year's theme is Arm in Arm, reflecting unity, resilience, and the vibrant spirit of the Filipino-American community.

22:54.311 --> 23:02.400
[SPEAKER_36]: On Saturday, September 13th, come to Point Furman Park for the music, stay for the food, and enjoy the company of fellow festival goers.

23:02.380 --> 23:11.911
[SPEAKER_36]: There'll be music and dance performances that bridge tradition and innovation on two stages, along with vendors, a first ever dog fashion show, and more.

23:12.492 --> 23:26.228
